---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Flourish from "../components/Flourish.astro";
import HeroSchematic from "../components/HeroSchematic.astro";
---

<Base title="snn — spiking networks as convex optimizers" width="wide">
  <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">

    <!-- ─────── Hero ─────── -->
    <section class="pt-2 sm:pt-6 pb-12 lg:pb-16 grid lg:grid-cols-[1.1fr_0.9fr] gap-10 lg:gap-16 items-center">
      <div class="order-2 lg:order-1">
        <p class="eyebrow mb-5 flex items-center gap-3">
          <span class="inline-block w-6 h-px bg-[--color-accent] opacity-60"></span>
          A friendly tour
          <span class="text-[--color-soft] tracking-normal normal-case font-normal">·</span>
          <span class="text-[--color-soft] tracking-normal normal-case font-normal italic" style="font-family: var(--font-serif);">v0.1</span>
        </p>
        <h1 class="text-[2.6rem] sm:text-[3.4rem] lg:text-[4rem] leading-[0.98] mb-7 -tracking-[0.022em]"
            style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 144, 'SOFT' 50; font-weight: 400;">
          Spiking neural<br/>
          networks <em class="italic" style="font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 144, 'SOFT' 100;">are</em><br/>
          <span class="text-[--color-accent]">convex optimizers.</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-[--color-muted] mb-9 max-w-xl leading-[1.55]"
           style="font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 22;">
          A simple population of leaky integrate-and-fire neurons,
          with the right connectivity, solves a quadratic program.
          Each spike is a constraint becoming active. Each silence is
          a gradient step. The page below walks through the idea, the
          math, and a runnable Python implementation.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3 items-center">
          <a
            href="/intro/"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-5 py-2.5 rounded-md bg-[--color-fg] text-[--color-bg] no-underline text-sm font-medium hover:bg-[--color-accent] transition-colors"
            style="font-family: var(--font-sans);"
          >
            Start with the intuition
            <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 14 14" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <path d="M2 7h10M8 3l4 4-4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
            </svg>
          </a>
          <a
            href="https://github.com/ahkhan03/SNN_opt"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-5 py-2.5 rounded-md border border-[--color-rule-strong] text-[--color-fg] no-underline text-sm font-medium hover:border-[--color-accent] hover:text-[--color-accent] transition-colors"
            style="font-family: var(--font-sans);"
          >
            View <code class="bg-transparent border-0 p-0 text-inherit text-[0.9em]">snn_opt</code> on GitHub
            <svg width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <path d="M3.5 2.5h6v6M9.5 2.5L2.5 9.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.4" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
          </a>
        </div>

        <!-- Tiny meta-strip: lineage / status. -->
        <dl class="mt-10 grid grid-cols-3 gap-6 max-w-md text-sm" style="font-family: var(--font-sans);">
          <div>
            <dt class="text-[--color-soft] text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-1">Pkg</dt>
            <dd class="text-[--color-fg]"><code class="bg-transparent border-0 p-0 text-[0.95em]">snn_opt</code></dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt class="text-[--color-soft] text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-1">Deps</dt>
            <dd class="text-[--color-fg]">NumPy · SciPy</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt class="text-[--color-soft] text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-1">License</dt>
            <dd class="text-[--color-fg]">Apache-2.0</dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
      </div>

      <div class="order-1 lg:order-2">
        <HeroSchematic />
        <p class="text-xs text-[--color-soft] mt-3 max-w-sm leading-relaxed"
           style="font-family: var(--font-sans);">
          A 2-D quadratic with three half-space constraints. The trajectory
          drifts toward <span class="italic" style="font-family: var(--font-serif);">x*ᵤ</span>,
          spikes at each active wall, and settles at the constrained
          optimum.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <Flourish />

    <!-- ─────── The idea, in three beats ─────── -->
    <section class="py-10">
      <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-[1fr_3fr] gap-8 mb-10">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow mb-3">Three beats</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl -tracking-[0.014em]"
              style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 60; font-weight: 500;">
            The idea, distilled.
          </h2>
        </div>
        <p class="text-[--color-muted] text-lg leading-[1.55] self-end max-w-xl"
           style="font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 22;">
          The whole framework collapses into three repeating moves.
          Everything else — the convergence proofs, the hardware story,
          the spike raster — falls out of these.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-px bg-[--color-rule] border border-[--color-rule] rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
        {[
          {
            n: "01",
            title: "Drift",
            body: "Between spikes, each neuron's membrane voltage moves by the gradient of an objective. Plain gradient descent — dressed up as biology.",
          },
          {
            n: "02",
            title: "Spike",
            body: "When the voltage would push the trajectory past a constraint, a spike fires. The spike re-projects the state onto the feasible boundary — a discrete correction.",
          },
          {
            n: "03",
            title: "Settle",
            body: "The spike train and the drift balance at the constrained optimum. Active spikes encode the active constraint set. The math is exactly that of a primal-dual QP solver.",
          },
        ].map((beat) => (
          <div class="bg-[--color-bg] p-7 lg:p-8 group">
            <div class="flex items-baseline gap-3 mb-4">
              <span class="font-mono text-xs text-[--color-accent] tabular-nums">{beat.n}</span>
              <span class="flex-1 h-px bg-[--color-rule]"></span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl mb-3" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 36; font-weight: 600;">
              {beat.title}.
            </h3>
            <p class="text-[--color-muted] text-[0.97rem] leading-[1.6]">
              {beat.body}
            </p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <Flourish />

    <!-- ─────── The picture ─────── -->
    <section class="py-10">
      <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-[1fr_3fr] gap-8 mb-10">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow mb-3">A picture</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl -tracking-[0.014em]"
              style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 60; font-weight: 500;">
            What it<br/>looks like.
          </h2>
        </div>
        <p class="text-[--color-muted] text-lg leading-[1.55] self-end max-w-xl"
           style="font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 22;">
          A 4-D quadratic, optimum outside a box constraint. The trajectory
          bounces against the four "active" faces every iteration; each
          dot is one projection event. Below it: the objective gap
          collapsing on the same iteration axis.
        </p>
      </div>
      <figure class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-[--color-rule] bg-white shadow-[var(--shadow-card)]">
        <img
          src="/figures/02_spike_raster.png"
          alt="Projection-spike raster on a 4-D box-constrained QP"
          class="w-full h-auto"
        />
        <figcaption class="px-5 py-3 text-xs text-[--color-muted] border-t border-[--color-rule] bg-[--color-paper]"
                    style="font-family: var(--font-sans);">
          <strong class="text-[--color-fg] font-semibold">Top:</strong> spike raster, one row per inequality, dot size ∝ projection magnitude.
          <strong class="text-[--color-fg] font-semibold ml-1">Bottom:</strong> objective gap on the same iteration axis.
          Generated by <code class="text-[--color-fg]">benchmarks/02_spike_raster.py</code>.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <Flourish />

    <!-- ─────── What you'll find here ─────── -->
    <section class="py-10">
      <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-[1fr_3fr] gap-8 mb-10">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow mb-3">Map</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl -tracking-[0.014em]"
              style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 60; font-weight: 500;">
            What you'll<br/>find here.
          </h2>
        </div>
        <p class="text-[--color-muted] text-lg leading-[1.55] self-end max-w-xl"
           style="font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 22;">
          Four entry points. Pick whichever matches your appetite — the
          intuition essay, the hands-on tutorials, the published papers,
          or the source code itself.
        </p>
      </div>

      <ul class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 not-prose list-none ml-0">
        {[
          {
            href: "/intro/",
            label: "Intro",
            kicker: "essay · 8 min",
            body: "The spiking idea explained from scratch, with no prior neuromorphic background required.",
          },
          {
            href: "/tutorials/",
            label: "Tutorials",
            kicker: "hands-on",
            body: "Walkthroughs: formulating SVMs, ridge regression, PCA and a few control problems as QPs you can drop into the solver.",
          },
          {
            href: "/papers/",
            label: "Papers",
            kicker: "peer-reviewed",
            body: "The published work that uses this framework, with abstracts and DOI links.",
          },
          {
            href: "https://github.com/ahkhan03/SNN_opt",
            label: "snn_opt repo",
            kicker: "source · Apache-2.0",
            body: "Canonical Python implementation: solver, examples, benchmarks, full mathematical writeup.",
            external: true,
          },
        ].map((c) => (
          <li>
            <a
              href={c.href}
              class="block p-6 bg-[--color-bg] border border-[--color-rule] rounded-lg no-underline relative overflow-hidden group transition-all duration-200 hover:border-[--color-accent] hover:-translate-y-0.5 hover:shadow-[var(--shadow-card-hover)]"
            >
              <span class="absolute left-0 top-0 bottom-0 w-1 bg-[--color-accent] origin-bottom scale-y-0 group-hover:scale-y-100 transition-transform duration-300"></span>
              <div class="flex items-start justify-between gap-4 mb-3">
                <span class="text-xl text-[--color-fg]" style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 36; font-weight: 600;">
                  {c.label}
                  {c.external ? (
                    <svg class="inline-block ml-1 -translate-y-0.5" width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                      <path d="M3.5 2.5h6v6M9.5 2.5L2.5 9.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.4" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                    </svg>
                  ) : null}
                </span>
                <span class="text-[0.65rem] uppercase tracking-widest text-[--color-soft] mt-1 shrink-0" style="font-family: var(--font-sans);">
                  {c.kicker}
                </span>
              </div>
              <p class="text-[--color-muted] text-sm leading-relaxed mb-0">
                {c.body}
              </p>
            </a>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </section>

    <Flourish />

    <!-- ─────── For whom ─────── -->
    <section class="py-10 lg:py-16">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <p class="eyebrow mb-4">For whom</p>
        <h2 class="text-3xl mb-6 -tracking-[0.014em]"
            style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-variation-settings: 'opsz' 60; font-weight: 500;">
          Who this is for.
        </h2>
        <p class="text-[--color-fg] text-lg mb-4 leading-[1.6]">
          Students starting a thesis on neuromorphic methods. Researchers
          from optimization or control who heard "spiking networks" and
          weren't sure what to make of it. Anyone who finds beauty in
          connections between fields that look unrelated until they don't.
        </p>
        <p class="text-[--color-muted] leading-[1.65]">
          If you want the formal version: head to the
          <a href="https://github.com/ahkhan03/SNN_opt"><code>snn_opt</code> repository</a>
          — it has the full theory document, an academic-style README, and
          a benchmark suite. The pages here are the
          <em>friendly</em> version of the same material.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

  </div>
</Base>
